The "largest city in Europe" may not have a consistent definition across countries, and may also depend on the criteria used to determine size and population.

Here is a function that takes a country code as an input and returns the largest city in that country as a string:

```
const largestCityInEurope = countryCode => {
  const largestCity = {};

  const cities = Object.values(citiesByCountry[countryCode]);

  cities.forEach(city => {
    if (largestCity.hasOwnProperty(city)) {
      largestCity[city] = largestCity[city] || 0;
    } else {
      largestCity[city] = 1;
    }
  });

  return Object.keys(largestCity).reverse().join(' ');
};
```

This function uses the "citiesByCountry" object to retrieve the list of cities in the given country, and uses a forEach loop to check if a city with the given name exists in the largestCity object. If it does not, the city is added with a default value of 0.

The largestCity object is then sorted in reverse order, and the keys of the sorted object are used to create a string containing the cities in the given country in alphabetical order.
